! AudioSuite — A ~TiddlyWiki Plugin for Audio Annotation, Playback & Transcription

''Plugin path:'' `$:/plugins/NoteStreams/AudioSuite`
''Author:'' ~NoteStreams

---

!! Overview

AudioSuite is a comprehensive ~TiddlyWiki plugin that turns your wiki into a powerful audio workstation for podcast listening, audiobook consumption, and deep audio annotation. It provides a suite of interconnected widgets that let you play audio tracks, capture timestamped notes on the fly, visually edit audio regions on a waveform canvas, and transcribe selections using the ~OpenAI Whisper API — all natively inside ~TiddlyWiki.

Each annotation is stored as its own atomic tiddler with structured fields (timecodes, tags, parent references), making your notes fully searchable, filterable, and transcludable across your wiki.

---

!! Features

* ''Podcast / Audiobook Player'' — Playlist-driven audio player with persistent playback position, playback rate control, chapter navigation, and virtual track support
* ''Tap & Hold Capture'' — Tap the capture button for a point annotation; hold it down for a time-range annotation. Auto-pauses playback and rewinds on resume
* ''Timestamped Notation System'' — Each note is an atomic tiddler tagged to its parent, with start/end timecodes, indent level, and custom tags. Notes render with clickable timecode badges that seek the player
* ''Waveform Editor'' — A canvas-based visual editor for precise region selection with draggable handles, scrub audio, snap-to-silence, amplitude zoom, minimap overview, undo/redo, and keyboard nudging
* ''Region Transcription'' — Send a selected audio region to ~OpenAI Whisper for speech-to-text, with optional GPT-powered post-editing for readability
* ''Sound Effects Widget'' — Lightweight widget for one-shot audio playback, snippet playback, and event-triggered sounds
* ''Palette-Aware Theming'' — All visual components read colors from the active ~TiddlyWiki `$:/palette`, CSS custom properties, or sensible defaults
* ''Audiobook Mode'' — Chapter navigation, auto-advance on track end, virtual tracks from data-dictionary tiddlers, and per-book position tracking
* ''Keyboard Shortcuts'' — Extensive shortcut support across the player (`Space`, `N`, arrows, `[`/`]`) and waveform editor (`←`/`→`, `S`, `T`, `Ctrl+Z`)
* ''Mobile Support'' — Pointer event handling, a capture modal for mobile note-taking, and touch-friendly UI

---

!! Installation

Install as a standard ~TiddlyWiki plugin by importing or dragging the plugin tiddler into your wiki. The plugin registers the following module types automatically:

|!Module Type |!Files |h
|`library` |`audio-utils.js`, `waveform-renderer.js`, and supporting modules (`audio-cache.js`, `audio-loader.js`, `mp3-parser.js`, `wav-encoder.js`, `peaks-generator.js`) |
|`widget` |`podcast-player-widget.js`, `audio-notation-widget.js`, `waveform-editor-widget.js`, `sound-effects-widget.js` |

After installation, save and reload your wiki. The four widgets become available as `<$podcast-player>`, `<$audio-notation>`, `<$waveform-editor>`, and `<$sound-effect>`.

---

!! Widgets Reference

---

!!! `<$podcast-player>`

The main audio player widget. Loads a playlist of audio tiddlers via a ~TiddlyWiki filter, provides transport controls, and emits capture events for the notation widget.

---

!!!! Attributes

|!Attribute |!Default |!Description |h
|`filter` |`""` |~TiddlyWiki filter returning audio tiddler titles. If omitted, the widget renders an interactive filter-entry UI. |
|`srcField` |`""` |Field name on each track tiddler that points to the audio source (e.g., `src`, `url`). Falls back to `_canonical_uri`, `canonical_uri`, `src`, `url`, or inline base64. |
|`class` |`""` |Additional CSS class(es) for the container. |
|`persistPosition` |`"yes"` |Whether to save/restore playback position per track. Stored in the `audio-track-position` field on the track tiddler. |
|`saveInterval` |`5` |Seconds between periodic position saves (minimum 2). |
|`autoPause` |`"yes"` |Pause playback automatically when a capture is made. |
|`rewindOnResume` |`3` |Seconds to rewind when playback auto-resumes after capture. |
|`enableShortcuts` |`"yes"` |Enable keyboard shortcuts on the player container. |
|`mode` |`"podcast"` |Set to `"audiobook"` for chapter navigation, auto-advance, and book-tiddler tracking. |
|`bookTiddler` |`""` |(Audiobook mode) Title of the book tiddler for storing current chapter and positions. |
|`debug` |`""` |If non-empty, shows the native `<audio>` element with controls for debugging. |

---

!!!! Capture Workflow

* ''Tap'' the 📌 Capture Note button → creates a ''point annotation'' at the current time
* ''Press and hold'' (>300ms) → enters ''range capture'' mode; release to set the end time
* Captures emit the `AudioSuite:timecode-captured` event, which the `<$audio-notation>` widget listens to

---

!!!! Keyboard Shortcuts

|!Key |!Action |h
|`Space` |Play / Pause |
|`N` |Quick capture (point annotation) |
|`←` / `→` |Rewind / Forward 10s |
|`Shift+←` / `Shift+→` |Rewind / Forward 30s |
|`[` / `]` |Decrease / Increase playback rate |

---

!!!! Child Widget Context

The player sets the `currentTiddler` variable to the currently playing track, and `bookTiddler` to the configured book tiddler. Nest `<$audio-notation>` (or any widget) inside `<$podcast-player>` to inherit these variables:

```
<$podcast-player filter="[tag[Podcast Episodes]]" srcField="audio-file">
  <$audio-notation />
</$podcast-player>
```

---

!!!! Virtual Tracks (Audiobook Mode)

In audiobook mode, the player scans tiddlers of type `application/x-tiddler-dictionary` that are tagged with the `bookTiddler` tiddler title. Each key-value pair maps a virtual track title to an audio URL. Virtual tracks appear in the playlist alongside real tiddlers. Playback positions for virtual tracks are stored as a JSON map in the `audio-track-positions` field on the book tiddler.

---

!!! `<$audio-notation>`

Displays and manages timestamped annotations for a given audio tiddler. Each annotation is stored as a separate tiddler, tagged with the parent tiddler and linked via a `parent-tiddler` field.

---

!!!! Attributes

|!Attribute |!Default |!Description |h
|`tiddler` |`<<currentTiddler>>` |The parent tiddler whose annotations to display. |
|`editable` |`"yes"` |Enable inline editing (double-click to edit). |
|`class` |`""` |Additional CSS class(es). |
|`extraTags` |`""` |Space-separated tags to add to every new notation tiddler. |
|`bookTiddler` |`<<bookTiddler>>` |Book tiddler for audiobook context fields. |
|`updateParent` |`"yes"` |Whether to update the parent tiddler's text with transclusion wikitext. |

---

!!!! Notation Tiddler Schema

Each notation tiddler has the following fields:

|!Field |!Description |h
|`title` |Auto-generated (configurable template, see below) |
|`parent-tiddler` |Title of the audio tiddler this note belongs to |
|`audio-source` |Resolved audio source (pointer tiddler title or URL) |
|`start-seconds` |Numeric start time in seconds |
|`end-seconds` |Numeric end time in seconds |
|`start-timecode` |Formatted start time (e.g., `05:23`) |
|`end-timecode` |Formatted end time |
|`indent` |Outliner indent level (0-based) |
|`tags` |Parent tiddler title + config tags + user tags |
|`text` |The note content (plain text with `[[wikilinks]]` support) |
|`cover` |(Audiobook) Book tiddler title |
|`structure` |(Audiobook) Parent tiddler title |

---

!!!! Inline Editor

* ''Double-click'' an entry to open the inline editor
* ''Ctrl+Enter'' saves; ''Escape'' cancels
* ''Tab'' / ''Shift+Tab'' increases / decreases indent level
* ''Tags'' can be added per-entry via the tag input field
* ''Delete'' removes the notation tiddler entirely
* ''📄 button'' opens the notation tiddler in the story river via `tm-navigate`

---

!!!! Mobile Capture Modal

On mobile devices, captures open a modal dialog for entering the note text and tags, rather than opening the inline editor directly.

---

!!!! Wikilink Support

Note text supports ~TiddlyWiki-style wikilinks: `[[Target Tiddler]]` and `[[Target|Display Text]]`. These render as clickable links that navigate via `tm-navigate`.

---

!!!! Parent Tiddler Updates

When `updateParent` is `"yes"`, the widget writes a managed block of wikitext into the parent tiddler, enclosed in `<!-- AudioSuite:notations:start -->` / `<!-- AudioSuite:notations:end -->` markers. This block contains `<$link>` and `<$transclude>` widgets for each notation, enabling the notes to appear in the parent tiddler's rendered output.

---

!!!! Legacy Migration

If the parent tiddler contains old-format `[MM:SS] text` lines, the widget automatically migrates them to atomic notation tiddlers on first render.

